<TITLE> Schroders 2007 profit up 35 pct, sees tougher 2008 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, March 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - UK fund management firm Schroders said on Tuesday that its 2007 pretax profit rose 35 percent but it expects a tougher environment for its business due to continued market volatility. Pretax profit rose to 392.5 million pounds ($779.2 million), from 290.0 million pounds in 2006, helped by sales of higher-margin products. Assets under management rose to 139.1 billion pounds at end-December from 128.5 billion pounds a year earlier, boosted by strong retail net inflows in Asia Pacific and the UK. "We expect ... volatile market conditions to persist through much of 2008 and as a result we envisage a less favourable environment for our business," the firm said in a statement to the Stock Exchange. In October, the firm posted a higher-than-expected rise in third-quarter profit but said the market environment would become more challenging. A number of fund firms have warned of tougher conditions following the onset of the credit crisis last summer, which has hit investor confidence and fund flows across the industry. Schroders increased its final dividend to 21 pence per share from 17.5 pence, bringing the total dividend for 2007 to 30 pence. Last year Schroders, which traces its roots back more than 200 years, said it was very open-minded about selective small acquisitions but ruled out any transformational de
